{"key":"processedPost-12966240","value":{"id":12966240,"first":12952420,"last":13028034,"when":1280337950,"utime":"07/28/10 08:25 PM","cleanedPost":"I haven't been following this thread closely, but just saw something above that freaked me the hell out.<br /><b>Do NOT spray insecticides on your mushrooms</b>.&nbsp; After harvest, which you should have done by now anyway, all you have to do is bump the mushrooms on a table a few times and the bugs will get knocked off.&nbsp; We grow a lot of outdoor mushrooms and they're always covered with small bugs of one kind or another.&nbsp; They're easy to get rid of as said above.&nbsp; Mushrooms absorb water, so any water based pesticide will be absorbed right into the fruit.&nbsp; I doubt seriously anyone wants to eat nerve toxins.<br />It's bad enough when apple growers spray their fruits, but in that case the toxins stay on the surface where 'most' can be rinsed off.&nbsp; Not so with mushrooms which will absorb the poison and then transfer it directly to your liver when you eat them.&nbsp; Think about that while you're tripping and it won't be pleasant.&nbsp; If you've already sprayed the damn things, toss them out.&nbsp; The spray is a thousand times worse than any bug.<br />RR"}}